ony, Retroactivity, and Ambiguity: Three Kinds of "Unreliable Narration" in Literature and Film / rBrütsch, Matthias -- t(Un)reliability in Fictional and Factual Audiovisual Narratives on YouTube / rKuhn, Markus -- tTracing Televised 'Truth': Reality Effect and Unreliable Narration in TV News / rBietz, Christoph -- tInterdisciplinary Perspectives On (Un)Reliability -- t(Un)reliable Narration in Journalism: The Fine Line between Fact and Fiction / rDernbach, Beatrice -- tUnreliable Narratives in the US Elections: How Much Reliability Can a Campaign Take? / rElter, Andreas -- tUnreliable Narration in Law Courts / rArnauld, Andreas Von / Martini, Stefan -- tUnreliable Narration in Historical Studies / rJaeger, Stephan -- tUnreliability in Patient Narratives: From Clinical Assessment to Narrative Practice / rMildorf, Jarmila -- tCommunicating Dreams: On the Struggle for Reliable Dream Reporting and the Unreliability of Dream Reports / rBoothe, Brigitte / Stojković, Dragica -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex  aThough the phenomenon known as "unreliable narration" or "narrative unreliability" has received a lot of attention during the last two decades, narratological research has mainly focused on its manifestations in narrative fiction, particularly in homodiegetic or first-person narration. Except for film, forms and functions of unreliable narration in other genres, media and disciplines have so far been relatively neglected. The present volume redresses the balance by directing scholarly attention to disciplines and domains that narratology has so far largely ignored. It aims at initiating an interdisciplinary approach to, and debate on, narrative unreliability, exploring unreliable narration in a broad range of literary genres, other media and non-fictional text-types, contexts and disciplines beyond literary studies. Crossing the boundaries between genres, media, and disciplines, the volume acknowledges that the question of whether or not to believe or trust a narrator transcends the field of literature: The issues of (un)reliability and (un)trustworthiness play a crucial role in many areas of human life as well as a wide spectrum of academic fields ranging from law to history, and from psychology to the study of culture.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 4aUnreliable narration. 4aintermedial/transgeneric narratology. 70(DE-601)1052141670(DE-588)4195138-4aUnzuverlässigkeit2gnd 70(DE-601)1055343820(DE-588)4152967-4aErzähler2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aNünning, Vera, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2015z9783110438673oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104084160 cprintz978311040810240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110408263423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110408263.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2015  aZDB-23-DKUb2015